# Ischial Tuberosity

> The **ischial tuberosity** is the roughened posterior bony projection of the ischium (part of the [[Hip Bone]]) on which you sit. It is the origin of the **hamstring muscles** and the adductor magnus.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Hip Bone]] — posteroinferior ischium
- [[Hamstrings|Biceps Femoris]] — long head originates here
- [[Hamstrings|Semitendinosus]] — originates here
- [[Hamstrings|Semimembranosus]] — originates here
- [[Adductor Magnus]] — hamstring portion originates here
- [[Sacrotuberous Ligament]] — connects ischial tuberosity to sacrum

## 🗂️ Key Facts
| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Common name | "Sit bone" |
| Palpation | Palpable when hip is flexed; protected by gluteus maximus when standing |
| Bursa | Ischial bursa overlies it |

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Hamstring avulsion fracture** — Forceful hip flexion with knee extension avulses the hamstring origin (sprinters, gymnasts); requires surgery if displaced
- **Ischial bursitis (weaver's bottom)** — Chronic compression of ischial bursa in sedentary individuals
- **Proximal hamstring tendinopathy** — Chronic pain at ischial tuberosity; common in cyclists and rowers

